not managed through the ExternallyManagedAppManager), but they have

PrefetchDocumentManager::DidStartNavigation() in serving time,

anyway doesn't call `SetNoVarySearchData()` and thus

`MatchUrl()` doesn't return No-Vary-Search matching results,

so this doesn't change the behavior in usual cases.

entry.title: [Shortcut] Use web app id for browser shortcut id.
entry.content:
This CL updates the code to use web app id for browser shortcut id.

Normally shortcut id should be a hash of the parent app id and the local

shortcut id. However, for web app based shortcut, it will be much easier

to continue using the existing id provided from web app provider, so

that we do not need to migrate all the sync data in app list and shelf.

And for web app based shortcut, the parent app is the browser, which

make sense to be handled as an exception case.

entry.title: DOM: Fix Observable error reporting behavior
entry.content:
Observables need to have the behavior where errors — via

`Subscriber#error()` or `throw`n exceptions — are "reported" to the

global [1] in two interesting corner cases:



1. After a subscription is already closed, yet the subscribe callback

continues to generate via `Subscriber#error()` or by `throw`ing an

exception

2. When `Subscribe#error()` is called but there is no

`Observer#error()` handler passed into the `subscribe()` method. In

this case, we must surface error in *some* way, and we do this by

reporting the exception to the global.



This CL also adds "detached document" tests, ensuring that none of the

`Observer` dictionary callbacks (`next()`, `complete()`, `error()`) are

invoked in a detached context, and further asserts that when

`Subscriber#error()` is invoked from a detached context specifically

when there is no `Observer#error()` handler passed-in, no exception is

reported to the global, because it is detached.



After this CL, there is a single remaining failing test of the existing

Observable constructor test. This asserts that `throw`n errors are

pushed to the Observer's `error()` handler if it exists, instead of

unconditionally "reported" to the global — this is because if the

`error()` handler does exist, that is the proper channel to funnel it

through. A subsequent CL will fix this behavior.



[1]: https://html.spec.whatwg.org/C#report-the-exception

entry.title: WebNN: Introduce reusable compute resources for DirectML backend
entry.content:
This CL introduces the reusable `ComputeResources` class that optimizes

the graph execution performance for DirectML backend.



`ComputeResources` contains the GPU resources for a graph execution,

including the descriptor heap, upload buffer, input buffer, output

buffer, read-back buffer and temporary buffer if the graph needs. The

compute resources are pre-allocated after graph initialization and

recycled after graph execution has been done. It avoids the resources

allocation overhead for the first execution and following executions

when it is available.



According to the test results of WebNN MobileNetV2 image classification

sample [1], it can reduce ~20% inference time on an integrated GPU and

~50% inference time on a discrete GPU.



[1]: https://webmachinelearning.github.io/webnn-samples/image_classification/index.html



Bug: 1273291

entry.title: Fix PDF Printing Issue with Missing File Extension
entry.content:
When printing a PDF, if the file name entered for the first time

contains special characters, the system refuses to save the file.

Then reverting to the normal filename (without the extension),

the resulting saved PDF file will be missing the file extension.

This CL solution where a default file extension is passed when

calling SelectFile().

This ensures that the PDF file is saved with the correct file

extension when the above situation occurs.

entry.title: Explicitly layout caption buttons at the end of animation
entry.content:
Instead of relying on the same animation progression to layout the

position and visibility of the buttons, the animation ended callback

will now explicitly set the position and visibility based on whether

or not the size button should be visible. This should make the code

more robust regardless of call ordering or restructuring (i.e.: we

might get janky animations, but the final positioning and visibility

should be correct).



Previously, the visibility of the code was highly dependent on the

animation state. Even though this *should* be in sync with

CaptionButtonModel, there are tiny windows where it is possible that

the animation could return that it is neither showing nor hiding,

which can lead to an undefined behaviour.

AXObjects will only be updated while processing deferred events,
